06582nam a22009375i 9789048543595DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1175277662  a97890485435957 a10.1515/97890485435952doi  a(DE-B1597)546150  a(OCoLC)1138675383  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a946.0100aFraming Power in Visigothic Society :bDiscourses, Devices, and Artifacts /ced. by Céline Martin, Eleonora Dell' Elicine. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLate Antique and Early Medieval Iberia ;v700tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- t1. Texts, Discourses, and Devices: Reading Visigothic Society Today -- t2. Presence of Augustine of Hippo in Isidore of Seville : Some Provisional Remarks -- t3. The Bishop and the Word: Isidore of Seville and the Production of Meaning -- t4. Unearthing Peasant Societies : Historiography and Recent Contributions in the Archaeology of the Rural World during Visigothic Times -- t5. Excolentes sacra fontium vel arborum: Pagan Cults, Kinship, and Regimes of Sacralization in the Visigothic Kingdom of Toledo -- t6. Ervig and Capital Penalties: The Way of Exile -- t7. ‘Put All Your Trust in Ansemundus’ : A Look at Distrust in Visigothic- Byzantine Diplomatic Relations -- t8. Visigothic Currency: Recent Developments and Data for Its Study -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume examines how power was framed in Visigothic society and how a diverse population with a complex and often conflicting cultural inheritance was thereby held together as a single kingdom. Indeed, through this dynamic process a new, early medieval society emerged. Understanding this transformation is no simple matter, as it involved the deployment of an array of political and cultural resources: the production of knowledge, the appropriation of Patristic literature, controlling and administering rural populations, reconceptualizing the sacred, capital punishment and exile, controlling the manufacture of currency, and defining Visigothic society in relation to other polities such as the neighbouring Byzantine state. In order to achieve an analysis of these different phenomena, this volume brings together researchers from a variety of disciplines. This interdisciplinary approach therefore expands the available sources and reformulates topics of traditional scholarship in order to engage with a renewal of Visigothic Studies and reformulate the paradigm of study itself. As a result, this volume rethinks frameworks of power in the Peninsula along not only historical and archaeological but also anthropological terms, presenting the reader with a new understanding of Iberian society as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aVisigoths. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLaw. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEarly Medieval Spain, Visigothic Society, Late Antiquity, Early Medieval History.1 aCastro, Dolores, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDell' Elicine, Eleonora, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDell’ Elicine, Eleonora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElfassi, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Céline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Céline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPliego, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTejerizo, Ca